---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout
  title="Horsepower vs Kilowatts: Car Power Explained"
  description="What HP and kW mean for your vehicle. Learn how to convert between horsepower and kilowatts with simple formulas."
  keywords="horsepower vs kilowatts, HP to kW, car power conversion, engine power, kW to HP, brake horsepower, vehicle power"
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <!-- Breadcrumb -->
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Power</span>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Horsepower vs Kilowatts: Car Power Explained" />

      <!-- Article Meta -->
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2025-06-12">June 12, 2025</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>4 min read</span>
      </div>

      <!-- Lead Paragraph -->
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Car manufacturers list power in different units depending on the market. Understanding HP and kW helps you compare vehicles from different countries and make informed decisions.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: The Conversion -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-6 my-6 not-prose shadow-sm">
        <p class="text-center text-xl font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">
          1 HP = 0.7457 kW | 1 kW = 1.341 HP
        </p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">
          Quick trick: HP × 0.75 ≈ kW | kW × 1.34 ≈ HP
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: What They Mean -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">What Do They Actually Mean?</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Horsepower (HP):</strong> Invented by James Watt to market steam engines. One HP is roughly the power output of a horse. Used in the US, UK, and Japan</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Kilowatt (kW):</strong> The SI unit of power. Used in Europe, Australia, and most of the world. Also used for electric vehicles globally</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>PS (Pferdestärke):</strong> German metric horsepower, slightly different from imperial HP. 1 PS = 0.9863 HP</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: Common Car Powers -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Common Car Powers</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Vehicle Type</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">HP</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">kW</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">City car</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">70-90</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">52-67</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Family sedan</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">150-200</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">112-149</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Sports car</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">300-500</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">224-373</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Supercar</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">600-1000+</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">447-746+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Tesla Model 3 LR</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">346</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">258</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: EVs and kW -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Electric Vehicles and kW</h2>
      <p>Electric vehicles have made kW more mainstream because:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Battery capacity</strong> is measured in kWh (kilowatt-hours)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Charging speed</strong> is measured in kW</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Motor output</strong> is naturally measured in kW</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>It makes more sense to use the same unit family throughout</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: Power vs Torque -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Power vs Torque</h2>
      <p>Power (HP/kW) is only half the story. Torque (Nm or lb-ft) determines how quickly a car accelerates from low speeds. A diesel truck might have more torque than a sports car despite having less horsepower.</p>

      <!-- Converter CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-50 to-orange-50 dark:from-amber-900/20 dark:to-orange-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">
            🔗 Try our free power converter
          </p>
          <a
            href="/convert/power"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 hover:bg-amber-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm"
          >
            Open Converter →
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Back to Blog -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">
          ← Back to all articles
        </a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
